I create an off screen buffer (image).  The first time I open a gc on it the a drawFocus() does not cause any problems with drawing. Subsequent creating of new gc's the drawFocus() causes problems in drawing.

I've distilled it down to the following sample. In it I am painting the background white (fillRectangle), then draw a focus rectangle (drawFocus), followed by filling and drawing a circle above the focus rectangle. The first time this is executed you will see the a circle with red outline and filled in blue, behind it there is the focus rectangle. After about 1/2 sec, a new gc is created on the off screen image, but this time the circle is not filled in with blue.

If you uncomment out the drawRectangle() this somehow enables the drawFocus to work correctly. The problem seems as if the new gc something isn't initialized correctly. Could something from the old gc be hanging around?

This occurs on a Nokia 9500 Communicator and the device emulator.

public static void main(String[] args) {
  final Display display = new Display();
  final Shell shell = new Shell(display);
  shell.setSize(523, 200);
  shell.open();

  Command commandExit = new Command(shell, Command.EXIT, 2);
  commandExit.setText("Exit");
  commandExit.addSelectionListener(new SelectionListener() {
    public void widgetSelected(SelectionEvent e) {
      shell.dispose();
    }
    public void widgetDefaultSelected(SelectionEvent e) {
    }
  });

  final Image img = new Image(display, 150, 150);

  Runnable runnable = new Runnable() {
    public void run() {
      if (!shell.isDisposed()) {
        GC gc = new GC(img, SWT.NONE);
        gc.setBackground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_WHITE));
        gc.setForeground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_WHITE));
        gc.fillRectangle(0, 0, 150, 150);
        // gc.drawRectangle(0, 0, 150, 150);
        gc.drawFocus(50, 50, 51, 51);
        gc.setBackground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_BLUE));
        gc.fillOval(50, 50, 50, 50);
        gc.setForeground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_RED));
        gc.drawOval(50, 50, 50, 50);
        gc.dispose();

        GC rgc = new GC(shell);
        rgc.drawImage(img, 0, 0);
        rgc.dispose();
        display.timerExec(500, this);
      }
    }
  };
  display.timerExec(500, runnable);

  shell.redraw();
  while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
    if (!display.readAndDispatch())
      display.sleep();
  }
  img.dispose();
  display.dispose();
}

